I played in a sectional this weekend with a quasi-expert partner.  He
has over 5000 mps, has played for 40 years or so, has written a local
bridge magazine for many years, etc.  He also is a master
&quot;resulter&quot;.
He:  AJT843  A6  AK  Q42
Me:  K6  QJ  87632  AK87
MPs all white, opponents passing throughout:
1S  -  3NT (showing 13-15, usually exactly 2 spades, I guess could be
3 spades)
4NT - all pass
Heart lead, ducked to the King on my right, heart return.  I played
rho for Qxx of spades, and made 6. ( I played the Js quickly at trick
3 and watched my rho for &quot;tells&quot;, if RHO had played smoothly and
seemingly without problems, I was gonna rise with the king and play
LHO for the queen.) 10 out of 12 matchpoints.  He went on and on about
how I should have bid 2C or 2D, and how we should have found 6S.  He
said I shouldn't distort my hand, and I should have every other suit
stopped to bid 3NT.  I think with his hand I would bid 6S over 3NT. I
think that considering my awful diamond suit, treating my hand as a
balanced 13-15 is right.

Your thoughts ... ?

Rich Regan
