You may not like 3NT, which is at least in part a matter of
philosophy.
Of course jumping to 3NT is not scientific. It can loose in various
ways (partner is short in diamonds with clubs his second suit for
example), but it can also win, giving opponents little in return. 3NT
often makes on the wrong opening lead.
What I do not stomach is that the 3NT bid has anything to do with the
final contract.
I can not imagine a better assistance for bidding the spade slam from
the correct side than
3NT. It is blatantly obvious. After 3NT, 4NT is clearly wrong and 5S
an underbid, though better than 4NT.
Starting with 2C may cause opener to worry later about a singleton
spade opposite. Standard methods are not always good in distinguishing
between singleton and a doubleton support, which is crucial
here.

Rainer Herrmann
