A little bidding judgement is called for.
I bid 2C instead of 2D because if partner has four diamonds he will
bid 2D over 2C.
Further, I don't want partner to evaluate  Qx or Qxx in diamonds
opposite my five feeble diamonds as an asset. But I do want partner to
evaluate Qx or Qxx in clubs as a big asset. Please note that in my
bidding sequence I communicated where 10/13 of my hcp are. In your
bidding 3NT you communicated 0/13 = 0 where your hcp were located.

A old grand master bridge player in the ACBL Bridge Hall of Fame once
advised me &quot;Don't make bids unless your hand is perfect for it.&quot; When
your standards are sloppy like your 3NT bid you can cause your partner
to make a mistake.

Eric Leong

PS: If you must know, I generally play 3NT as a balanced four card
raise as per Kaplan.
I prefer 2NT as natural and forcing.
With more practiced partnerships, I like playing two-tiered
splinters. So 3NT would
show a better splinter then a direct splinter.
