Yes I do and for the same reason. When opener has something like: xxx,
x, AKx, AJTxxx, it is much better to have an auction like:
1C-2NT-3C... where you have a good chance to get to the right game
than guess after 1C-3NT.

Playing 2NT as forcing allows you to bid 2NT with either 13-15 or
18-19 and 3NT with exactly 16-17. This is a much better structure than
standard for describing balanced hands as responder.

Handling 11-12 Balanced
*  When the opening bid is 1C, you lose virtually nothing by playing
2NT as forcing, since you can temporize with 1D or, if you hold 4+
clubs, bid 2C inverted when holding 11-12 balanced.

*  When the opening bid is 1D, it is awkward to handle 11-12 balanced.
With 12 I stretch and bid 2NT with a bad 11 I bid a heavy 1NT. Bidding
only 1NT sounds scary, but in practice it works out. Partner only
passes 1NT with a balanced 12-14. With 12-13 he was passing my
invitational 2NT anyway so I am better off in 1NT. With 14 I may have
miss a marginal game, but very rarely a cold one. Fortunately, 11-12
with no four-card major and all three side suits stopped does not come
up often. You can also preemptively avoid this auction by opening 1C
more often. For example, with 4-4 in the minors.

Andrew
