Yes I do because all the same considerations apply. And there are
extra ways to win.

*  13-15 balanced = 2NT
16-17 balanced = 3NT
18-19 balanced = 2NT and later bid again

This is a much more accurate responding structure for balanced hands.

*  Suppose as responder you hold: KQx, QTxx, Qxx, KJx. If opener has a
balanced 12-14, 3NT is probably better than 4H even if you have a 4-4
fit. However if partner is unbalanced, 4H is probably better. If you
can bid a forcing 2NT, partner can raise to 3NT if balanced and rebid
3M if unbalanced with a 4-card major.

*  Suppose you hold: KQx, JTx, AJT, QTxx. It is much safer to respond
2NT than 3NT to show 13-15 because you have room to diagnose shortness
opposite your JTx.

Handling 11-12 balanced
*  After 1C opening.
Responder can temporize with 1D or raise to 2C, inverted if holding 4-
clubs.

*  After 1D opening.
Responder bids 2NT (forcing) with 12 and bids a heavy 1NT with a poor
11. This method is not as bad as it sounds. When opener is unbalanced
he will bid again. When opener has a balanced 12-14, you will be fine
when he holds 12-13. So the losing case is when opener has exactly 14
balanced and responder has exactly 11. Even in this losing case, you
will likely miss only a marginal not a cold game.

Andrew
